<font color="#FF0000">LITTLE THINGS</font><br>
<tt>Sat Mar  8  9:19:26 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Art,<br><br>
Slime mold races I don't recall. But, I remember the tedium that many days brought. We played a lot of cards such as spades and hearts.<br><br>
It may be odd to say this, but the hours of boredom and how we spent them say much about us.<br><br>
There are many who judge us, and events that transpired in Vietnam, without having any reference point in their individual lives with which to compare these events.<br><br>
You, being a former artilleryman, know what a reference point is. A reference point is a prominent feature. Those who stayed behind have nothing to compare with our Vietnam experience. This may sound elitist or exclusive, but it is reality.<br><br>
There are those who post to this channel under the guise of &quot;wanting to understand&quot;. It is a paradox that one can learn by *speaking* rather *listening* or asking questions.<br><br>
There was much tedium and boredom experienced in Vietnam. And those who are trying to get into our heads with their explanations and theories should understand that.<br><br>
Oh! I almost forgot. There were good things that were done and experienced by those who are continually portrayed as ruthless murderers. <br><br>
We know GOOD sells far fewer newspapers than EVIL.<br><br>

<p><code>-- wingman@greene.xtn.net  (Tom Dier) </code><p>


